<% page_title "Plain old Ruby objects, organised into domains" %>

<section class="hero">
  <div class="hero-copy">
    <p class="eyebrow">LUNA 01 / Domain-oriented Ruby</p>
    <p class="hero-kicker">You’ll never see the Lunula. It doesn’t exist.</p>
    <h1>The Lunula<br><span>must be built.</span></h1>
    <p class="lede">Lunula stays small enough to disappear into your
      application. You do not see a tower of framework machinery; you see plain
      old Ruby objects organised into domains, plus the tools needed to build
      the app you actually want.</p>
    <div class="hero-actions">
      <%= link "Build a blog in 10 minutes", "/guides/blog", class: "button button-primary" %>
      <%= link "Browse the Helium cookbook", "/guides/helium", class: "button button-secondary" %>
      <%= link "Read the full store guide", "/guides/store", class: "button button-secondary" %>
    </div>
  </div>
  <aside class="terminal" aria-label="Lunula quick start commands">
    <div class="terminal-bar"><span></span><span></span><span></span><b>~/projects</b></div>
    <pre><code><span class="prompt">$</span> gem install lunula
<span class="prompt">$</span> luna new field-notes
<span class="prompt">$</span> cd field-notes
<span class="prompt">$</span> bundle exec luna start

<span class="success">Lunula is open on :5151</span></code></pre>
  </aside>
</section>

<section class="manifesto" id="why">
  <header class="section-heading">
    <p class="eyebrow">Why Lunula</p>
    <h2>Small enough to understand.<br>Structured enough to keep.</h2>
  </header>
  <div class="feature-grid">
    <%= component :feature, number: "01", title: "Explicit by default",
      detail: "Routes are ordinary code. Action methods receive explicit context and params. Repositories use Sequel directly." %>
    <%= component :feature, number: "02", title: "Organised by domain",
      detail: "Plain old Ruby objects live where their behaviour belongs. Posts own their routes, behaviour, persistence, views and events." %>
    <%= component :feature, number: "03", title: "HTML first",
      detail: "Return a Hash and Lunula renders ERB. Idiomorph navigation makes pages feel immediate; Helium enhances only what moves." %>
    <%= component :feature, number: "04", title: "Ruby-shaped behaviour",
      detail: "Write Posts.publish(post), not PublishPost.call. Use modules, composition and plain objects instead of framework inheritance." %>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="code-story">
  <div class="code-story-copy">
    <p class="eyebrow">One request. No mystery.</p>
    <h2>The HTTP boundary stays thin.</h2>
    <p>An action receives request context and permitted parameters. Domain
      behaviour remains named for what the application actually does.</p>
    <button type="button" class="text-button" @click="showFiles = !showFiles">
      Toggle the domain filesystem
    </button>
    <pre class="file-tree" @visible="showFiles"><code><%= structure_example %></code></pre>
  </div>
  <pre class="code-panel"><code><%= request_example %></code></pre>
</section>

<section class="principles">
  <p class="eyebrow">The useful middle</p>
  <h2>More structure than a micro app.<br>Less machinery than a monolith.</h2>
  <div class="principle-list">
    <p><strong>Rack</strong><span>The web boundary remains standard Ruby.</span></p>
    <p><strong>Sequel</strong><span>Explicit datasets and repositories, never Active Record.</span></p>
    <p><strong>ERB + Helium</strong><span>Server HTML with progressive enhancement and no Node requirement.</span></p>
    <p><strong>Cookbook patterns</strong><span>Filtering, inline edits, modals, previews and pending states without a client-side app.</span></p>
    <p><strong>Batteries that matter</strong><span>Auth, mail, jobs, events, caching, uploads and security without a service-object empire.</span></p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="final-cta">
  <span class="catalogue-number">LUNA 01 / START HERE</span>
  <h2>Make the first page.</h2>
  <p>The ten-minute guide starts with a blank terminal and ends with a working CRUD blog.</p>
  <%= link "Build the blog", "/guides/blog", class: "button button-primary" %>
</section>
